ğŸ§  1. What Is the Stream API?
============================
â¤ The Stream API is a functional programming tool introduced in Java 8
for processing collections of data (like List, Set, Map, arrays, etc.) in a declarative and efficient way.

    Instead of writing loops and if conditions manually,
    Stream allows you to express data transformations in a pipeline of operations.


ğŸ” 2. Why Stream API?
======================
  -----------------------------------------------------------------------
| Traditional Approach                  | Stream API Approach             |
| ------------------------------------- | ------------------------------- |
| External Iteration (e.g., `for` loop) | Internal Iteration              |
| Imperative style                      | Declarative style               |
| Harder to parallelize                 | Easy parallel processing        |
| Mutates data                          | Non-mutating (functional style) |
  ------------------------------------------------------------------------


âš™ï¸ 3. Core Concepts of Stream API
======================================
3.1 Stream Definition
    A Stream represents a sequence of elements supporting sequential and parallel operations.

3.2 Stream Characteristics:
    - Not a data structure (does not store data)
    - Can only be used once
    - Lazy evaluation â€” operations are executed only when a terminal operation is called
    - Supports pipelined operations
    - Can be sequential or parallel



ğŸ§© 4. Stream Pipeline Components
==================================
A Stream pipeline has three parts:
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
| Part                           | Description                                  | Example                                |
| ------------------------------ | -------------------------------------------- | -------------------------------------- |
| 1. Source                      | Collection, array, generator, or I/O channel | `list.stream()`                        |
| 2. Intermediate Operations     | Transform or filter data                     | `.filter()`, `.map()`, `.sorted()`     |
| 3. Terminal Operation          | Produces a result or side-effect             | `.collect()`, `.forEach()`, `.count()` |
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------



ğŸª£ 5. Stream Creation (Sources) :
===============================
5.1 From Collections
5.2 From Arrays
5.3 From Static Methods
5.4 Infinite Streams

ğŸ”„ 6. Intermediate Operations (Transformations)
================================================
Intermediate operations return another Stream, allowing method chaining.
    6.1 filter(Predicate<T>) : Filters elements based on a condition.
    6.2 map(Function<T, R>) : Transforms each element to another form.
    6.3 flatMap(Function<T, Stream<R>>) : Flattens nested structures into a single stream.
    6.4 distinct() : Removes duplicates.
    6.5 sorted(), sorted(Comparator<T>) : Sorts stream elements.
    6.6 peek(Consumer<T>) : Used for debugging.
    6.7 limit(long n) and skip(long n) : Used for pagination or truncation.

    # flatMap() :
        ğŸ§© 1. The Core Idea
        ---------------------
            flatMap() is used to transform each element of a stream into another stream,
            and then flatten (merge) all those resulting streams into a single stream.

        ğŸ” 2. Problem it solves
        ------------------------
            Suppose you use .map(), and the function you pass returns a Stream.
            Youâ€™d then get a Stream of Streams â†’ Stream<Stream<T>>, which is hard to work with.
            flatMap() helps by flattening those nested streams into a single continuous stream.

            ğŸ§  3. Conceptual Difference Between map() and flatMap()
            ---------------------------------------------------------------------
            | Operation   | Input     | Function Result | Output                |
            | ----------- | --------- | --------------- | --------------------- |
            | `map()`     | Stream<T> | T â†’ R           | Stream<R>             |
            | `flatMap()` | Stream<T> | T â†’ Stream<R>   | Stream<R> (flattened) |
            --------------------------------------------------------------------



ğŸ¯ 7. Terminal Operations (End of Pipeline)
============================================
Terminal operations produce a result or side effect and consume the stream.










ğŸ”„ 12. Stream Lazy Evaluation
================================
Streams execute operations only when a terminal operation is invoked. Check coding example for more



ğŸ§ª 13. Common Stream Use Cases
===================================
âœ… Filtering records
âœ… Transforming data
âœ… Removing duplicates
âœ… Aggregating data (sum, count, max, min)
âœ… Grouping or partitioning
âœ… Parallel processing


